🏡 THE HOME LAND

Ubiquitous Language

Version: 1.0

⸻

Purpose

This document establishes the official business vocabulary used throughout The Home Land.

Every business discussion, document, database model, API, UI component, workflow, AI prompt, and source code must use these definitions consistently.

A single business concept must always have one official name.

Synonyms are prohibited unless explicitly defined.

⸻

Naming Principles

Rule 1

One concept.

One official name.

⸻

Rule 2

Business terminology has priority over technical terminology.

⸻

Rule 3

The UI, Database, API, Documentation, and Source Code must use identical terminology.

⸻

Rule 4

All official business terms are written in English.

Future localization must translate labels only, never business concepts.

⸻

Organization Domain

Organization

The legal business entity using the platform.

Examples:

* Property Company
* Landlord
* Real Estate Agency
* Enterprise Client

An Organization owns all business data.

⸻

Portfolio

A collection of properties managed by an Organization.

⸻

User

A person with authenticated access to the platform.

A User may have one or more roles.

⸻

Role

Defines permissions granted to a User.

Examples:

* SuperAdmin
* Owner
* Property Manager
* Accountant
* Maintenance Manager
* Tenant
* Vendor

⸻

Property Domain

Property

A real estate asset.

Examples:

* Apartment Complex
* Office Building
* Shopping Center
* Villa
* Warehouse
* Hotel

⸻

Building

A physical structure belonging to a Property.

A Property may contain multiple Buildings.

⸻

Floor

A subdivision of a Building.

⸻

Unit

A rentable or assignable space.

Examples:

* Apartment
* Office
* Retail Space
* Parking Space
* Storage Room

A Unit is never the same as a Property.

⸻

Amenity

A shared feature available to occupants.

Examples:

* Swimming Pool
* Gym
* Garden
* Conference Room
* Parking Area

⸻

Leasing Domain

Tenant

A person or organization occupying one or more Units.

⸻

Occupant

Any individual currently living or operating within a Unit.

An Occupant is not necessarily the Lease holder.

⸻

Lease

A legal agreement defining occupancy conditions.

⸻

Lease Renewal

Extension of an existing Lease.

⸻

Move-In

The official beginning of occupancy.

⸻

Move-Out

The official termination of occupancy.

⸻

Security Deposit

Funds collected to cover potential damages or contractual obligations.

⸻

